  {panel}

We are interested in a way of displaying all issues that were updated by an individual during a certain timeframe. 

For example, query all issues that were updated/modified by user in the last 2 weeks.

With the "Participant" field it gives all the ticket that was modified by anyone in the last 2 weeks, and that was also modified at some point by the user. but we need  a way to identify tickets that a user specifically updated 2 weeks ago.

This doesn't have any visible issues for the user, however it is something we should address in the code soon or it may lead to some issues.  It appears that the mail code doesn't use the "baseurl" set via the VelocityRequestContext, but it has its own baseurl passed in.

Here is one example: 
{code}
 mailingListCompiler.sendLists(recipientList, sender, getSenderFrom(event), emailSubject, templateId, (String) event.getParams().get("baseurl"), getIssueContextParams(event), threader);
{code}

The MailingListCompiler then uses a special method where the baseurl is passed along.  As far as I can tell, if contextParams already contains a baseurl it will override what's passed along:
{code}
String body = ManagerFactory.getVelocityManager().getEncodedBodyForContent(templateContent, baseUrl, contextParams);
{code}

In the mail code however, the contextParams do not contain a 'baseurl', since they get created via the {{JiraMailQueueUtils}} class, which does not set the baseurl like the {{JiraVelocityUtils}} class.  

Overall I think this is very confusing and *will* lead to bugs in the future.  I think we should:
* Get rid of the JiraMailQueueUtils and replace them with JiraVelocityUtils
* No longer call the method on the velocityManager that expects the baseUrl
* Use the baseurl set in the VelocityRequestContext (Care needs to be taken that this has the right value)

